      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Inbound links, external links</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Backlinks</strong> are links from other websites that point to a page on your site. Google treats them as votes of confidence: the more high-quality, relevant backlinks a page earns, the more likely it is to rank for its target keywords. They are one of Google's oldest and most durable ranking signals.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Signal type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-page authority</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google weight</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Core ranking factor</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Foundational</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If content is what you say, backlinks are who vouches for you. Google has been ranking pages partly on the count and quality of incoming links since 1998, and despite hundreds of algorithm updates, backlinks remain one of the top three ranking factors for competitive queries. Get them right and traffic compounds; get them wrong and you spend years cleaning up penalties.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are backlinks?</h2>
        <p>A backlink, sometimes called an inbound link or an incoming link, is any hyperlink on a third-party website that points to your site. From Google's perspective, each backlink is a signal that another site found your content worth referencing. When enough independent sites link to the same page for the same reasons, Google infers the page is authoritative on that topic.</p>
        <p>Every backlink has a few attributes Google reads:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Source domain</strong> &mdash; the site the link is on, and its own authority</li>
          <li><strong>Anchor text</strong> &mdash; the clickable words used to describe the destination</li>
          <li><strong>Link attributes</strong> &mdash; <code>rel="nofollow"</code>, <code>rel="sponsored"</code>, <code>rel="ugc"</code>, or dofollow (nothing)</li>
          <li><strong>Placement</strong> &mdash; body content, sidebar, footer, or navigation</li>
          <li><strong>Context</strong> &mdash; the topic of the linking page and how naturally the link fits it</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google has publicly ranked backlinks alongside content quality and RankBrain as the top three signals in its algorithm. In 2024 leaks and public statements confirmed that both quantity of referring domains and topical relevance shape rank &mdash; but only when the links come from trusted sources.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why backlinks matter</h2>
        <p>Every SEO team eventually confronts the same reality: content wins for easy queries; backlinks decide the competitive ones. Three reasons make them a permanent priority.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>PageRank still works.</strong> Google's original algorithm modelled the web as a graph of votes. Two decades later the mechanism is still central &mdash; pages with more (and better) incoming links outrank pages with fewer.</li>
          <li><strong>Topical authority builds slowly.</strong> A cluster of backlinks around related keywords tells Google your site is a subject-matter authority, unlocking rank for the whole topic, not just the linked page.</li>
          <li><strong>Referral traffic is a bonus.</strong> Beyond ranking, backlinks bring their own click-throughs from human readers on the source site &mdash; usually the highest-intent traffic you get.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How backlinks work</h2>
        <p>Google's crawler follows links to discover pages. Its indexer stores those links as edges in a graph. Its ranking system uses that graph &mdash; alongside on-page and query signals &mdash; to decide what to show.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The backlink signal loop</span><br>
          Site A publishes: <span class="uf-new">"See theStacc's guide on ARPU"</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          Google crawls Site A, finds <span class="uf-label">&lt;a href="thestacc.com/glossary/arpu/"&gt;</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          Link stored in graph &rarr; PageRank flow to destination<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          Anchor text (<span class="uf-status">"guide on ARPU"</span>) associated with destination topic<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&darr;<br>
          Destination ranks higher for related queries
        </div>

        <h3>Google evaluates quality, not just quantity</h3>
        <p>Ten links from mid-tier blogs will rarely beat one link from a top-tier publisher in the same niche. Google models quality through source authority, topical relevance, link position, and freshness. A links-per-referring-domain graph beats a raw link count every time.</p>

        <h3>The link equity flow</h3>
        <p>Each link passes a share of the source page's authority (PageRank / link equity) to the destination. Multiple outbound links on one page split the equity between them. Nofollow links reduce but do not eliminate that flow in Google's current model.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of backlinks</h2>
        <p>Not every link is equal. Understanding the categories helps you decide which to pursue and which to walk away from.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Description</th><th>SEO value</th><th>Effort</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Editorial dofollow</strong></td>
                <td>Journalist or blogger links to you naturally</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Highest</td>
                <td>High &mdash; via PR or original data</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Guest post</strong></td><td>You write on their site with an author bio link</td><td class="cell-meh">Medium (contextual body links higher)</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Resource page</strong></td><td>Curated list of tools/guides links to you</td><td class="cell-yes">High if relevant</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Directory / citation</strong></td><td>Business listing on Yelp, GMB, industry directory</td><td class="cell-meh">Low individually, high in aggregate for local SEO</td><td>Low</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Nofollow / UGC</strong></td><td>Forum, comment, or social profile link</td><td class="cell-meh">Referral + hint to Google</td><td>Low</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Paid / private network</strong></td><td>Purchased or PBN link</td><td class="cell-no">Risk of penalty</td><td>Should avoid</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real backlink examples</h2>
        <p>Three concrete plays that produce sustainable link growth.</p>

        <h3>1. Original research becomes a citation magnet</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Original data example</span><br>
          Publish: <span class="uf-new">"State of SaaS Pricing 2026: analysis of 400 companies"</span><br>
          Result: <span class="uf-status">180+ referring domains</span> in 12 months<br>
          Why: journalists cite the underlying number, not a talking point
        </div>

        <h3>2. Digital PR &mdash; a newsworthy angle on your data</h3>
        <p>Package a slice of internal data into a 300-word press-friendly story, pitch to five journalists on a beat that covers your space, and land coverage that includes editorial dofollow links. A single tier-one placement (Forbes, TechCrunch, The Verge) is often worth more than 100 low-tier links.</p>

        <h3>3. Guest posts on relevant industry blogs</h3>
        <p>Write for a publication your ICP already reads, with a link back to a relevant guide from within the body copy. Value comes from the editorial context, not the author-bio slot, so structure your pitch around a topic they were already going to publish.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Backlinks vs internal links &mdash; different jobs</h2>
        <p>Both are hyperlinks, but they carry different SEO signals.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Backlinks (external)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Come from third-party sites</li>
              <li>Google reads as third-party endorsement</li>
              <li>Pass PageRank between domains</li>
              <li>Build topical authority for your whole site</li>
              <li>Need earning, not just linking</li>
              <li>Slow to accumulate, hard to fake</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card" style="background: #ecfeff; border-color: #a5f3fc;">
            <h4 style="color: #0e7490;">Internal links</h4>
            <ul style="color: var(--text-1);">
              <li>Link between pages on the same site</li>
              <li>Google reads as site structure and priority</li>
              <li>Redistribute PageRank within your domain</li>
              <li>Signal which pages are most important</li>
              <li>Fully under your control</li>
              <li>Fast to change, easy to audit</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 backlink best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Earn, don't buy.</strong> Google is highly effective at detecting paid link patterns. The best backlinks come from things worth linking to, not link-building blasts.</li>
          <li><strong>Focus on referring domains, not total link count.</strong> One link each from 100 sites beats 100 links from one site.</li>
          <li><strong>Match anchor text to intent naturally.</strong> Over-optimized exact-match anchors are the fastest way to trigger Google's spam signals. A natural anchor distribution includes brand, generic ("click here"), and topical variants.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise topical relevance.</strong> A link from a mid-tier site in your niche often outperforms a link from a huge site that is off-topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Recover lost links.</strong> Broken-link recovery is the cheapest link-building play. Find dead links pointing at your site, restore or redirect them, and reclaim the equity.</li>
          <li><strong>Turn unlinked brand mentions into links.</strong> Set up alerts for your brand and reach out politely when someone mentions you without linking.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit new links monthly.</strong> Watch for sudden spikes of low-quality links; disavow only if you find a clear negative-SEO pattern.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap &mdash; the link-velocity myth</div>
          <p>Sudden bursts of 100+ new backlinks a week without a corresponding PR event or piece of viral content look unnatural to Google. Sustainable link building follows a slope, not a spike &mdash; and slow, boring, editorial links are the ones that keep rankings when the next algorithm update lands.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common backlink mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buying links.</strong> Public link marketplaces are the easiest source of penalties and the least durable source of rank.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing high-DR domains regardless of topic.</strong> A high-authority link from an off-topic site provides less value than Google's crawlers used to attribute.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the anchor text mix.</strong> An anchor profile that is 70% exact-match keyword screams manipulation.</li>
          <li><strong>Never checking who links to you.</strong> Bad neighbourhood links accumulate silently and can drag a domain down over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Confusing referring domains with total links.</strong> The domain count is the real leverage metric; total links is a vanity number.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many backlinks do I need to rank?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>There is no fixed number. Some pages rank with a handful of high-quality backlinks; competitive queries can require hundreds of referring domains. Match the average referring-domain count of the top three ranking pages for your target keyword.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can backlinks hurt my rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Low-quality, spammy, or paid links can trigger Google's algorithmic filters and, in rare cases, a manual penalty. Google's spam algorithms usually ignore bad links rather than penalise, but a heavy pattern of unnatural links is still a risk.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I check my backlinks?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Use Google Search Console for the free view of your backlink profile, or Ahrefs, Semrush, or Majestic for deeper analysis including referring domains, anchor text distribution, and lost/new links over time.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Are nofollow links worthless?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Google now treats nofollow as a hint rather than a strict directive and may still pass authority through certain nofollow links. They also drive referral traffic and brand mentions, which have their own SEO value.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long does it take for backlinks to affect rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google usually crawls new backlinks within days, but ranking impact often takes weeks to months as the link accumulates trust and other signals compound. Big spikes in one week rarely move rankings the same week.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

